00:38:03,534 --> 00:38:05,035
It's gonna be a great summer.

261
00:38:19,174 --> 00:38:22,010
- Why do you leave early?
- He always leaves early.

262
00:38:22,094 --> 00:38:25,347
- Do you have somewhere to go?
- See you tomorrow.

263
00:38:33,814 --> 00:38:35,899
Sorry I'm late.

264
00:38:37,985 --> 00:38:39,945
I got held up at school.

265
00:38:41,947 --> 00:38:43,657
I have a new book.

266
00:38:43,740 --> 00:38:46,910
The Lady with a Little Dog.

267
00:38:49,538 --> 00:38:50,789
By Anton Chekhov.

268
00:38:50,873 --> 00:38:54,168
"The talk was that a new face
had appeared on the promenade,

269
00:38:54,251 --> 00:38:56,420
a lady with a little dog. "

270
00:39:09,099 --> 00:39:11,602
Schmitz, one moment, please.

271
00:39:12,978 --> 00:39:17,149
I read the reports on you.
Every single one. Excellent work.

272
00:39:17,232 --> 00:39:19,818
You'll be working in the office.

273
00:39:19,902 --> 00:39:23,280
You got promoted. Congratulations.

274
00:39:30,454 --> 00:39:34,416
- Yee-haw!
- Ah!

275
00:39:34,500 --> 00:39:36,710
Let's get out of here!

276
00:39:36,793 --> 00:39:40,088
Come on! Michael, we're leaving.
Let's go!

277
00:39:40,172 --> 00:39:41,298
Come on, Michael!

278
00:39:41,381 --> 00:39:44,426
It's meant to be a surprise
for your birthday.

279
00:39:47,971 --> 00:39:50,182
- Come on!
- What's the matter?

280
00:39:50,265 --> 00:39:53,393
- I'm sorry. Really.
- We thought you'd like it.

281
00:39:53,477 --> 00:39:55,687
We've got beer!
We're gonna dance!

282
00:39:56,647 --> 00:39:57,773
I promised someone.

283
00:39:58,899 --> 00:40:00,901
Michael, please!

284
00:40:05,989 --> 00:40:09,660
"Here and there the reflection
of the stars and the lights,

285
00:40:09,743 --> 00:40:12,120
on the bank quivered and trembled. "

286
00:40:12,204 --> 00:40:14,915
- Oh, kid, kid.
- What?

287
00:40:14,998 --> 00:40:17,876
- Stop.
- What's wrong now?

288
00:40:17,960 --> 00:40:20,504
Nothing's wrong.

289
00:40:23,048 --> 00:40:24,842
It's nothing.

290
00:40:26,927 --> 00:40:30,347
You know, you never ask.

291
00:40:31,014 --> 00:40:33,976
You never bother to ask how I am!

292
00:40:34,059 --> 00:40:35,727
You never say.

293
00:40:37,020 --> 00:40:38,856
It just happens to be my birthday.

294
00:40:40,691 --> 00:40:43,443
It's my birthday, that's all!

295
00:40:43,527 --> 00:40:45,404
You've never
even asked when it is.

296
00:40:45,487 --> 00:40:48,157
- If you want a fight, kid...
- I don't want a fight!

297
00:40:48,240 --> 00:40:51,827
- What's wrong with you?!
- What business is it of yours?!

298
00:40:51,910 --> 00:40:55,289
It's always on your terms.
Everything.

299
00:40:55,372 --> 00:40:58,083
We do what you want.
It's always what you want.

300
00:40:58,167 --> 00:41:00,961
- My friends were giving me a party.
- Why are you here?

301
00:41:01,044 --> 00:41:04,715
Go back to your party.
Is that what you want?

302
00:41:07,050 --> 00:41:09,219
Mm! Mm!

303
00:41:30,365 --> 00:41:32,326
It's always me
that has to apologize.

304
00:41:32,409 --> 00:41:36,705
You don't have to apologize.
No one has to apologize.

305
00:41:45,422 --> 00:41:47,132
War and Peace, kid.

306
00:43:32,529 --> 00:43:34,740
Now, you must go
back to your friends.

307
00:43:50,923 --> 00:43:51,924
Are you all right?

308
00:45:23,098 --> 00:45:24,433
It's him.

309
00:45:28,353 --> 00:45:30,522
Good.

310
00:45:30,606 --> 00:45:32,900
Get the boy something to eat.

311
00:45:41,909 --> 00:45:45,496
I think we all knew you'd
come back to us eventually.

312
00:46:54,565 --> 00:46:57,734
Mr. Berg? It is 8:00.

313
00:46:57,818 --> 00:46:59,570
Your daughter.

314
00:47:02,239 --> 00:47:04,324
Thank you.

315
00:47:06,994 --> 00:47:08,829
Julia.

316
00:47:10,914 --> 00:47:14,001
- I've not kept you waiting?
- I was early.

317
00:47:14,084 --> 00:47:16,295
Welcome back.

318
00:47:19,047 --> 00:47:22,176
So how will you decide?

319
00:47:22,259 --> 00:47:25,053
I don't know.

320
00:47:25,137 --> 00:47:27,014
I'm happy back in Berlin, I suppose.

321
00:47:27,097 --> 00:47:29,266
- You've seen your mother?
- Mm-hmm.

322
00:47:29,349 --> 00:47:31,977
I wanted to get away. That's all.

323
00:47:32,060 --> 00:47:34,479
It was Paris,
but it could have been anywhere.

324
00:47:34,563 --> 00:47:37,024
Away from your parents?

325
00:47:38,901 --> 00:47:41,320
I'm aware I was difficult.

326
00:47:43,155 --> 00:47:44,990
I wasn't always open with you.

327
00:47:48,535 --> 00:47:50,829
I'm not open with anyone.

328
00:47:57,336 --> 00:47:58,921
I knew you were distant.

329
00:48:00,797 --> 00:48:05,719
You know...
I always assumed it was my fault.

330
00:48:06,803 --> 00:48:09,556
Julia.

331
00:48:09,640 --> 00:48:11,391
How wrong can you be?

332
00:48:23,153 --> 00:48:26,031
- I'll see you very soon.
- See you soon.

333
00:48:28,784 --> 00:48:31,328
- Good night, Dad.
- Good night.

334
00:48:39,086 --> 00:48:41,713
Those of you
for the special seminar group,

335
00:48:41,797 --> 00:48:43,090
please stay on in this room.

336
00:48:43,091 --> 00:48:43,924
please stay on in this room...

337
00:48:44,007 --> 00:48:46,760
Professor Rohl will
be here in a moment.

338
00:49:17,416 --> 00:49:22,296
Well, we seem
to be quite a small group.

339
00:49:22,379 --> 00:49:26,091
A small group and a select one.

340
00:49:26,175 --> 00:49:29,469
Clearly, this is going
to be a unique seminar.

341
00:49:29,553 --> 00:49:34,099
We are going to start
with a reading list, gentlemen.

342
00:49:34,183 --> 00:49:36,685
Karl Jaspers...

343
00:49:36,768 --> 00:49:41,064
- And ladies.
- ... The Question of German Guilt.

344
00:49:41,148 --> 00:49:45,068
Creation: Making Time

345
00:49:57,623 --> 00:50:00,626
So this is where you are.

346
00:50:00,709 --> 00:50:02,252
Yes.

347
00:50:04,046 --> 00:50:05,506
Come in.

348
00:50:07,591 --> 00:50:11,345
- You take work seriously.
- I don't know.

349
00:50:11,428 --> 00:50:13,847
You're rather a serious boy.

350
00:50:13,931 --> 00:50:16,016
It's how I was brought up.

351
00:50:17,601 --> 00:50:20,687
What about you? Are you serious?

352
00:50:23,565 --> 00:50:26,026
You're sure you want to work tonight?

353
00:50:27,569 --> 00:50:28,737
Yeah.

354
00:50:30,447 --> 00:50:32,115
But I won't work every night.

355
00:50:33,283 --> 00:50:34,827
See you tomorrow.

356
00:50:40,791 --> 00:50:43,919
- Yes. Exactly
- That's right.

357
00:50:48,715 --> 00:50:50,551
You need a hand.

358
00:51:15,409 --> 00:51:19,580
- Why all the police?
- They're worried about demonstrators.

359
00:51:19,663 --> 00:51:22,499
- For or against?
- Both.

360
00:51:27,963 --> 00:51:29,464
Wow. It's a circus.

361
00:51:32,718 --> 00:51:34,636
All rise.

362
00:51:37,222 --> 00:51:39,600
All photographers
are now asked to leave.

363
00:51:41,018 --> 00:51:43,812
This court is now in session.
Please sit down.

364
00:51:47,316 --> 00:51:49,818
First thing I'm going to do
is hear motions

365
00:51:49,902 --> 00:51:52,112
from each of the defendants' lawyers.

366
00:51:52,196 --> 00:51:55,991
They're arguing that there's
no reason to keep the defendants in jail

367
00:51:56,074 --> 00:51:58,785
until the outcome
of the forthcoming trial.

368
00:51:58,869 --> 00:52:01,497
- I'll take these cases one by one.
- Want a pen?

369
00:52:01,580 --> 00:52:04,875
- I got a pen.
- Hanna Schmitz.

370
00:52:06,543 --> 00:52:10,297
- Your name is Hanna Schmitz?
- Yes.

371
00:52:10,380 --> 00:52:12,758
Can you speak louder please?

372
00:52:12,841 --> 00:52:15,886
- My name is Hanna Schmitz.
- Thank you.

373
00:52:15,969 --> 00:52:21,808
- You were born on October 21st, 1922?
- Yes.

374
00:52:21,892 --> 00:52:23,685
At Hermannstadt.

375
00:52:23,769 --> 00:52:28,106
- And you're now 43 years old?
- Yes.

376
00:52:28,190 --> 00:52:33,278
- You joined the SS in 1943?
- Yes.

377
00:52:33,362 --> 00:52:35,906
What was your
reason for joining?

378
00:52:37,616 --> 00:52:40,744
You were working
at the Siemens factory at the time?

379
00:52:40,828 --> 00:52:41,912
Yes.

380
00:52:41,995 --> 00:52:44,581
You'd recently
been offered a promotion.

381
00:52:44,665 --> 00:52:46,500
Why did you prefer to join the SS?

382
00:52:46,583 --> 00:52:49,837
- Objection.
- I'll re-phrase my question.

383
00:52:49,920 --> 00:52:52,506
I'm trying to ascertain

384
00:52:52,589 --> 00:52:55,676
if she joined the SS freely, hmm?

385
00:52:55,759 --> 00:52:57,177
Of her own free will.

386
00:52:58,762 --> 00:53:02,349
- I heard there were jobs.
- Go on.

387
00:53:02,432 --> 00:53:05,227
I was working at Siemens

388
00:53:05,310 --> 00:53:08,564
when I heard the SS was recruiting.

389
00:53:08,647 --> 00:53:12,526
Did you know the kind of work
you'd be expected to do?

390
00:53:12,609 --> 00:53:16,196
They were looking for guards.

391
00:53:16,280 --> 00:53:20,534
- I applied for a job.
- You worked first at Auschwitz?

392
00:53:20,617 --> 00:53:23,871
- Yes.
- Until 1944.

393
00:53:23,954 --> 00:53:28,542
Then you were moved to
a smaller camp near Krakow?

394
00:53:28,625 --> 00:53:30,210
- Yes.
- Are you OK?

395
00:53:30,294 --> 00:53:33,046
- You helped move prisoners...
- I'm fine.

396
00:53:33,130 --> 00:53:36,592
...west in the winter of 1944
in the so-called death marches?

397
00:53:57,821 --> 00:54:01,533
- So, what did you think?
- I don't know.

398
00:54:02,784 --> 00:54:04,745
It wasn't quite what I was expecting.

399
00:54:04,828 --> 00:54:09,082
Wasn't it? In what way?
What were you expecting?

400
00:54:09,166 --> 00:54:11,502
I thought it was exciting.

401
00:54:11,585 --> 00:54:14,087
Exciting? Why?

402
00:54:14,171 --> 00:54:16,590
Why did you think it was exciting?

403
00:54:16,673 --> 00:54:18,425
Because it's justice.

404
00:54:47,663 --> 00:54:53,168
Societies think they operate
by something called morality,

405
00:54:53,252 --> 00:54:54,753
but they don't.

406
00:54:54,837 --> 00:54:59,174
They operate by something called law.

407
00:54:59,258 --> 00:55:04,888
You're not guilty of anything
merely by working at Auschwitz.

408
00:55:04,972 --> 00:55:08,225
Eight thousand people
worked at Auschwitz.

409
00:55:08,308 --> 00:55:13,814
Precisely 19 have been convicted,
and only six for murder.

410
00:55:13,897 --> 00:55:18,819
To prove murder,
you have to prove intent.

411
00:55:18,902 --> 00:55:20,737
That's the law.

412
00:55:20,821 --> 00:55:24,533
The question is never was it wrong,

413
00:55:24,616 --> 00:55:27,494
but was it legal.

414
00:55:27,578 --> 00:55:32,332
And not by our laws, no.

415
00:55:32,416 --> 00:55:36,503
- By the laws at the time.
- But isn't that...

416
00:55:36,587 --> 00:55:39,089
- What?
- ... narrow?

417
00:55:39,173 --> 00:55:43,051
Oh, yes. The law is narrow.

418
00:55:44,052 --> 00:55:46,180
On the other hand,

419
00:55:46,263 --> 00:55:49,725
I suspect people who kill other people

420
00:55:49,808 --> 00:55:53,437
tend to be aware that it's wrong.

421
00:55:54,521 --> 00:55:55,272
Miss Schmitz,
you're familiar with this book?

422
00:55:55,273 --> 00:55:58,942
Miss Schmitz,
you're familiar with this book?!

423
00:56:01,069 --> 00:56:03,322
- Yes.
- Parts of it

424
00:56:03,405 --> 00:56:05,866
have already been
read out in court.

425
00:56:05,949 --> 00:56:08,535
It's by a survivor,

426
00:56:08,619 --> 00:56:10,537
a prisoner who survived.

427
00:56:10,621 --> 00:56:13,332
Ilana Mather.

428
00:56:13,415 --> 00:56:16,043
She was in the camp
when she was a child, wasn't she?

429
00:56:16,126 --> 00:56:18,837
- She was with her mother.
- Yes.

430
00:56:18,921 --> 00:56:23,217
In the book,
she describes a selection process.

431
00:56:23,300 --> 00:56:26,345
At the end of the month's labor,
every month,

432
00:56:26,428 --> 00:56:29,473
sixty inmates were selected.

433
00:56:29,556 --> 00:56:33,060
Picked out to be sent from
the satellite camp back to Auschwitz.

434
00:56:33,143 --> 00:56:35,062
That's right, isn't it?

435
00:56:36,438 --> 00:56:38,649
Yes, that's right.

436
00:56:38,732 --> 00:56:42,110
And, so far,
each of your fellow defendants

437
00:56:42,194 --> 00:56:44,988
has specifically denied
being part of that process.

438
00:56:45,072 --> 00:56:49,034
Now, I'm going to ask you.

439
00:56:49,117 --> 00:56:50,494
Were you part of it?

440
00:56:52,996 --> 00:56:54,039
Yes.

441
00:56:57,626 --> 00:57:01,213
So you helped make the selection?

442
00:57:01,296 --> 00:57:04,299
- Yes.
- You admit that?

443
00:57:09,763 --> 00:57:12,933
Then tell me,

444
00:57:13,016 --> 00:57:15,435
how did that selection happen?

445
00:57:15,519 --> 00:57:18,188
There were six guards,

446
00:57:18,272 --> 00:57:22,901
so we decided we'd
choose ten people each.

447
00:57:24,486 --> 00:57:27,114
That's how we did it every month.

448
00:57:27,197 --> 00:57:29,449
We'd all choose ten.

449
00:57:29,533 --> 00:57:32,244
Your fellow defendants
took part in the process?

450
00:57:32,327 --> 00:57:35,080
We all did.

451
00:57:35,164 --> 00:57:37,791
Even though they've denied it?

452
00:57:37,875 --> 00:57:41,628
Saying "we," "we all"
is easier than saying "I," "I alone,"

453
00:57:41,712 --> 00:57:43,380
isn't it, Miss Schmitz?

454
00:57:45,048 --> 00:57:48,051
Did you not realize

455
00:57:48,135 --> 00:57:50,971
that you were sending
these women to their deaths?

456
00:57:51,054 --> 00:57:54,683
But they were new arrivals,
new women were arriving all the time.

457
00:57:54,766 --> 00:57:59,480
So... the old ones had to make room
for the new ones.

458
00:58:00,731 --> 00:58:04,234
- I'm not sure you understand...
- We couldn't keep everyone.

459
00:58:04,318 --> 00:58:06,737
- There wasn't room.
- No.

460
00:58:06,820 --> 00:58:09,740
But what I'm saying...

461
00:58:09,823 --> 00:58:12,576
Let me rephrase.

462
00:58:12,659 --> 00:58:15,496
To make room, you were
picking women out and saying,

463
00:58:15,579 --> 00:58:20,167
"You, you and you have
to be sent back to be killed. "

464
00:58:20,250 --> 00:58:22,711
Well, what would you have done?

465
00:58:33,263 --> 00:58:35,724
Should I never
have signed up at Siemens?

466
00:58:48,195 --> 00:58:51,782
Ms. Mather,
they're ready for you now.

467
00:58:54,201 --> 00:58:56,787
Go, go. Go, go, go.

468
00:59:08,257 --> 00:59:10,968
- Where's Michael?
- I don't know.

469
00:59:12,302 --> 00:59:16,890
In your book, you describe
the process of selection.

470
00:59:16,974 --> 00:59:18,559
Yes.

471
00:59:18,642 --> 00:59:22,563
You were made to work and then,
when you were no longer any use to them,

472
00:59:22,646 --> 00:59:26,066
then they sent you back
to Auschwitz to be killed.

473
00:59:26,150 --> 00:59:29,027
Are there people here
who made that selection?

474
00:59:29,111 --> 00:59:30,946
Yes.

475
00:59:31,029 --> 00:59:36,493
I need you to identify them.
Can you please point them out?

476
00:59:49,173 --> 00:59:50,883
Her.

477
00:59:54,386 --> 00:59:55,762
And her.

478
00:59:58,307 --> 00:59:59,766
Her.

479
01:00:02,144 --> 01:00:04,146
And her.

480
01:00:06,148 --> 01:00:08,066
Her.

481
01:00:10,235 --> 01:00:11,862
And her.

482
01:00:13,489 --> 01:00:16,366
Thank you. Please continue.

483
01:00:16,450 --> 01:00:19,995
Each of the guards would choose
a certain number of women.

484
01:00:20,078 --> 01:00:22,247
Hanna Schmitz chose differently.

485
01:00:22,331 --> 01:00:24,875
In what way differently?

486
01:00:29,463 --> 01:00:31,715
She had favorites.

487
01:00:33,342 --> 01:00:35,093
Girls, mostly young.

488
01:00:35,177 --> 01:00:37,971
We all remarked on it.

489
01:00:38,055 --> 01:00:41,266
She gave them food
and places to sleep.

490
01:00:41,350 --> 01:00:45,938
In the evening,
she... she asked them to join her.

491
01:00:46,021 --> 01:00:47,606
And we all thought...

492
01:00:47,689 --> 01:00:50,692
Well, you can imagine
what we thought.

493
01:00:50,776 --> 01:00:56,406
And then we found out she was making
these women read aloud to her.

494
01:00:59,076 --> 01:01:01,245
They were reading to her.

495
01:01:02,454 --> 01:01:07,000
At first, we thought this guard,
this guard is...

496
01:01:07,084 --> 01:01:11,880
...more sensitive,
she's more human, she's kinder.

497
01:01:12,756 --> 01:01:16,176
Often, she chose the weak, the sick.

498
01:01:17,886 --> 01:01:21,223
She picked them out.
She seemed to be protecting them almost.

499
01:01:21,306 --> 01:01:23,892
But then she dispatched them.

500
01:01:26,854 --> 01:01:28,939
Is that kinder?

501
01:01:37,781 --> 01:01:40,909
I want to
move on now to the march.

502
01:01:40,993 --> 01:01:45,038
As I understand it, you and your
daughter were marched for many months.

503
01:01:45,122 --> 01:01:49,293
In the winter of 1944,
our camp was closed down.

504
01:01:49,376 --> 01:01:54,381
We were told we had to move on.
But the plan kept changing every day.

505
01:01:54,464 --> 01:01:58,218
Women were dying
all around us in the snow.

506
01:01:58,302 --> 01:02:02,890
Half of us died on the march.
My daughter says in the book,

507
01:02:02,973 --> 01:02:06,268
"Less a death march,
more a death gallop. "

508
01:02:07,936 --> 01:02:12,024
Please tell us about
the night in the church.

509
01:02:19,823 --> 01:02:24,495
That night, we thought we were lucky
because we had a roof over our heads.

510
01:02:24,578 --> 01:02:27,414
Go on.

511
01:02:27,498 --> 01:02:30,584
We'd arrived in a village.

512
01:02:30,667 --> 01:02:35,130
As always, the guards took the best
quarters. They took the priest's house.

513
01:02:35,214 --> 01:02:38,675
But they let us sleep in a church.

514
01:02:38,759 --> 01:02:42,262
There was a bombing raid
in the middle of the night.

